<h4>Behaviour</h4>
<p><strong>Assessment (Behaviour):</strong> Excellent</p>
<p><strong>Comment:</strong><br>
Hugo is a motivated and attentive student who consistently brings a positive attitude to class. He is always calm, polite, and happy to participate, creating a welcoming atmosphere for both classmates and the teacher. His enthusiasm for activities—such as the Dice Game, drawing, and explaining expressions—demonstrates his engagement and enjoyment of the learning process. Hugo is highly cooperative, willingly accepts corrections, and actively seeks clarification when unsure. His supportive nature, including helping peers like Nina with spelling, further enriches the classroom environment.</p>

<h4>Work</h4>
<p><strong>Assessment (Work):</strong> Very good</p>
<p><strong>Comment:</strong><br>
Hugo approaches his work with dedication and seriousness. He completes exercises thoroughly, reviews key concepts like articles in texts, and participates eagerly in all activities. His ability to summarize chapters, form questions, and use target language structures—such as "would rather…than…" and "prefer…to…"—reflects his strong effort and responsibility. While he occasionally requires inspiration or guidance, such as clarifying the purpose of connectors, he consistently demonstrates a willingness to improve. His attentive and fun-loving attitude makes him a pleasure to teach.</p>

<h4>Performance</h4>
<p><strong>Assessment (Performance):</strong> Good</p>
<p><strong>Comment:</strong><br>
Hugo shows a solid understanding of the material, particularly in reading, listening, and using grammatical structures. He performs well in exercises, fills in gaps accurately during listening tasks, and can report characters' dialogue effectively. His knowledge of vocabulary and sentence formation is good, though he sometimes struggles with pronunciation (e.g., repeating corrected words) and persistent errors, such as omitting the 's' in third-person singular verbs or misusing articles. While he occasionally makes tense mistakes (e.g., "didn’t found") or spelling errors (e.g., "wich" for "which"), he nearly always corrects himself when prompted or realizes his mistakes independently. His ability to discuss topics like food groups, school rules, and music demonstrates growing fluency, though he benefits from occasional support to expand his vocabulary usage.</p>

<h4>Marks</h4>
<p><strong>Oral Performance:</strong><br>
Hugo communicates with increasing confidence and clarity. His pronunciation has improved, though occasional mistakes persist, particularly with verb endings and articles. He expresses himself well in structured tasks, such as riddles and discussions about stories, and shows a strong ability to self-correct. To further enhance his fluency, he should focus on internalizing connectors (e.g., "although," "despite") and expanding his active vocabulary. Regular practice in spontaneous speaking will help him reduce hesitation and refine his accuracy.</p>

<p><strong>Written Performance:</strong><br>
